# Audio Reactivity Audit and Implementation Plan

Date: 2026-05-05
Scope: Preset Studio separation of Image audio reactivity vs Preset (MilkDrop) audio reactivity

## 1) Conversation decision audit (locked requirements)

The user requirement is now clear and explicit:

1. Image audio reactivity must remain exactly as it is.
2. Motion tab needs an Image-style reactivity interface.
3. Motion reactivity must affect MilkDrop presets only (imported packs + scratch presets).
4. Motion controls must not alter Image layer reactivity behavior.
5. Keep audio reactivity capability for presets; do not remove it.

This plan is built to those requirements.

## 2) Code audit summary (current behavior)

### A. Image tab reactivity is mature and isolated at layer-logic level

Image controls write per-layer state and are consumed in image-layer GLSL generation.
Current image reactivity fields include:

- reactSource
- reactCurve
- audioPulse
- bounceAmp
- shakeAmp
- opacityPulse
- strobeAmp
- strobeThr

These are baked in _buildImageBlock(img) and apply per image layer.

### B. Motion tab "Reactivity" is currently mixed with global controls

Current Motion tab controls are:

- Energy -> engine.energyMultiplier (session)
- Bass Sensitivity -> engine.baseSensitivity (session)
- Beat Sensitivity -> baseVals.b1ed (preset)
- Auto gain control -> engine.agcEnabled (session)

This creates UX confusion because the section is named like preset-level reactivity but includes engine-level conditioning.

### C. Why users perceive cross-coupling

Image and Preset logic paths are separate, but both read the same analyzed audio bands.
Global conditioning (AGC/Energy/Bass Sensitivity) changes upstream signal intensity, so both can feel stronger/weaker even though settings are separate.

## 3) Target architecture (best for app + user control)

This is the recommended direction.

1. Preserve Image tab exactly (no behavior or wiring changes).
2. Add Preset-only Motion reactivity controls that mirror Image UX:
	- Source (Bass/Mid/Treble/Volume)
	- Curve (Linear/Squared/Cubed/Gate)
	- Per-target modulation amounts for preset motion fields.
3. Apply Motion reactivity as an overlay on MilkDrop preset motion values only.
4. Keep global input-conditioning controls separate from creative tab semantics.

Result:

- Imported preset packs keep identity but gain controllable extra motion reactivity.
- Scratch presets get the same predictable control model.
- Image layer behavior remains untouched.

## 4) Implementation plan (safe sequence)

### Phase 1: Separation contract and state model

1. Add new preset-level motion reactivity state object in editor state.
2. Keep all existing image fields unchanged.
3. Keep persisted compatibility: defaults produce zero added modulation.

Proposed state sketch:

- motionReact.enabled
- motionReact.source
- motionReact.curve
- motionReact.zoomAmt
- motionReact.rotAmt
- motionReact.warpAmt
- motionReact.warpSpeedAmt
- motionReact.driftXAmt
- motionReact.driftYAmt

### Phase 2: Motion tab UI upgrade (Image-style UX)

1. Replace current Motion "Reactivity" block with Source + Curve + target sliders.
2. Keep Beat Sensitivity as preset-owned control (still valid).
3. Move Energy/Bass Sensitivity/AGC to a clearly named Global Audio section (outside Motion semantics).

### Phase 3: Preset-only modulation engine

1. Implement modulation in preset generation/apply path only.
2. Derive one shaped signal from source + curve.
3. Apply only to MilkDrop motion parameters (zoom/rot/warp/etc) with clamps.
4. Do not touch image-layer shader logic or image state reads.

### Phase 4: Compatibility and guardrails

1. Imported presets with no new motionReact state should render unchanged by default.
2. Scratch presets with defaults should render unchanged until user turns up sliders.
3. Add clamps to prevent runaway values and visual breakage.

## 5) Verification checklist (must-pass)

Image safety checks:

1. Image Source/Curve/Pulse/Bounce/Shake/Beat Fade/Strobe behavior unchanged.
2. Existing saved presets with image layers render identically before/after with motionReact defaults.

Preset-only checks:

1. Imported pack preset responds to new Motion Reactivity sliders.
2. Scratch preset responds the same way.
3. Turning Motion reactivity to zero restores base preset motion exactly.

Separation checks:

1. Changing Motion reactivity does not alter any image layer control values.
2. Image tab edits do not alter motionReact values.

## 6) Decision

Yes, this is the best path for app clarity and user control:

1. Preserve the proven Image system.
2. Add equal-quality Preset reactivity UX in Motion.
3. Enforce strict separation by architecture, not just labeling.

## 7) Approval gate before code changes

If approved, implementation starts with Phase 1 + Phase 2 scaffolding, then Phase 3 modulation wiring.

Reply with: yes or go ahead.

## 8) Implementation status (completed on 2026-05-05)

Completed:

1. Motion tab now includes a preset-only Source + Curve + modulation slider interface.
2. Motion tab no longer hosts AGC/Energy/Bass Sensitivity controls (global conditioning removed from Motion semantics).
3. Preset-only runtime modulation is injected via frame_eqs overlay at load time for editor preview.
4. Works for imported presets and scratch presets because modulation is applied to the active preset state before loadPresetObject().
5. Image tab reactivity code path was not modified.

Notes:

1. Modulation defaults are all zero, preserving backward-compatible visual output until user enables Motion reactivity.
2. Gate curve uses a clamp-based shaping expression to avoid parser-specific conditional syntax risk.

## 9) Forward tracking location

For all follow-on session-level input/performance work (Global tab, calibration, runtime stability), use:

- [docs/performance-control-roadmap.md](docs/performance-control-roadmap.md)

This keeps future development separate from the Motion/Image reactivity implementation notes in this file.
